Part I - Prosper Loan Analysis¶

by Greatness Okeremeta¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

# Reorder the IncomeRange , EmploymentStatus, ProsperRating columns as ordered categorical variables
inc_dict = {'IncomeRange': ['Not displayed', 'Not employed', '$1-24,999', 
                           '$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74,999', '$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+'],
           'EmploymentStatus': ['Employed', 'Self-employed', 'Full-time',
                                'Part-time', 'Other', 'Retired'],
           'ProsperRating':['HR', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A', 'AA']}
for i in inc_dict:
    order = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories = inc_dict[i])
    subset_df[i] = subset_df[i].astype(order);

The structure of the dataset¶

The main data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables

The main features of interest in the dataset¶

My investigation aims to answer the following questions:

  1. What features can be used to explain/predict default on credit?
  2. What correlation exists between the number of loans and income range?
  3. What is the relationship between borrower rate and loan amount?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your features of interest?¶

The Prosper rating and employment status will be essential in investigating the possiblity of default. Other useful features in the data are the loan amount and terms, borrower rate and income.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most of the borrowers are employed and a majority of the loans are current loans. Interest rates are rightly-skewed. Most of the loans are undertaken by people who earn at least \$25,000.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There was a sharp peak in the interest rate around 0.32 which was significantly higher than the other interest rates. I created a subset of the main dataset to make investigation easier. Some columms were renamed to ensure that the data set is neatly displayed. Null values in the Prosper rating column were dropped as they'd affect the analysis being conducted. The IncomeRange , EmploymentStatus, ProsperRating columns were also reordered to allow for them to be displayed appropriately as categorical variables.

Loan Status, Loan Original Amount and Prosper Rating¶

In [32]:
# Adjusting the Loan Status to only display Completed and Defaulted loans

setting = (subset_df['LoanStatus'] == 'Completed') | (subset_df['LoanStatus'] == 'Defaulted') |\
                  (subset_df['LoanStatus'] == 'Chargedoff')
subset_df = subset_df[setting]

#define a function to adjust the loan status to 2 values
def change(status):
    if status['LoanStatus'] == 'Chargedoff':
        return 'Defaulted'
    else:
        return status['LoanStatus']
    
subset_df['LoanStatus'] = subset_df.apply(change, axis=1)
subset_df['LoanStatus'].value_counts()

Listing Category, Loan Original Amount and Loan Status¶

In [34]:
Listing_categories = {1: 'Debt Consolidation', 2: 'Home Improvement', 3: 'Business',  
                      4: 'Personal Loan', 5: 'Student Use', 6: 'Auto', 7: 'Other'}
def minimize(categories):
    loan_category = categories['ListingCategory']
    if  loan_category in Listing_categories:
        return Listing_categories[loan_category]
    else:
        return Listing_categories[7]

# Check  
subset_df['ListingCategory'] = subset_df.apply(minimize, axis=1)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Most of the defaulted credits were loans obtained for home improvement. These loans were the only loan category that saw more defaults than completion. As loan amount increased, so did the Prosper rating. This isnt surprising as the borrowers who take on heavier loans, tend to earn more based on data from the previous sections, they also have better Prosper ratings. They would get lower interest rates, it is assumed that they can afford to pay higher monthly payments, the negative correlation between the interest rate and the loan original amount supports this. It was also noticed that the borrowed amounts increased in the last few years, while the average interest rate decreased.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It was interesting to see that the defaulted loans for individuals with high Prosper ratings tend to be larger than completed loans. One would expect that these individuals would have a higher number of completed loans since the data suggests that they earn more than the others. For people in the \$1 - \\$24,999 income range, the sharp decline in their APR in 2013 was noteworthy, it became the lowest APR for all income groups in the year.

Conclusions¶

In exploring the data, I found a strong negative correlation between the loan amount and the borrowers interest rate; the higher the loan amount, the smaller the interest rate. The largest number of loans fell between 0.1 and 0.3 borrowers rate. Most of the loans in the data set are current loans, followed by completed and charged-off loans. I also discovered an overwhelming amount of active loans to be past their due date by 1 - 15 days.

A significant number of borrowers had only 1 prior loan while a few individuals had 2+ prior loans. Of the 3 available loan terms, the 36 month tenor was the most-preferred. The loan original amount steadily increased from 2009 to 2012 for all income groups. In 2013, the unemployed borrowers had a sharp drop in their loan original amounts.

For multivariate exploration, the loan status was modified to display completed and defaulted loans. It was interesting to see that the defaulted loans for individuals with high Prosper ratings tend to be larger than completed loans. One would expect that these individuals would have a higher number of completed loans since the data suggests that they earn more than the others.
